    <item>
  <title>Oops, it did it again: Another small hydrothermal explosion at Biscuit Basin</title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/observatories/yvo/news/oops-it-did-it-again-another-small-hydrothermal-explosion-biscuit-basin?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>Early on the morning of Saturday, June 13, 2026, a small hydrothermal explosion occurred at Biscuit Basin in Yellowstone National Park.&nbsp;Although smaller than the explosion that occurred in the same area in 2024, it emphasizes the dynamic and hazardous nature of hydrothermal activity in the region.</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Mon, 22 Jun 2026 00:30:00 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>mpoland@usgs.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">bd56efaa-2e76-41df-a37b-548f2bfaa261</guid>
    <author>mpoland@usgs.gov (mpoland@usgs.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>Volcano Watch — What is the difference between an eruption and an episode?</title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/observatories/hvo/news/volcano-watch-what-difference-between-eruption-and-episode?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>Over the last year and a half, the historic episodic eruption at the summit of Kīlauea has had 49 episodes of lava fountaining, with episode 50 in the forecast for next week. But why are these individual fountaining events considered episodes instead of separate eruptions, and what’s the difference?</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Fri, 19 Jun 2026 04:25:04 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>kmulliken@usgs.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">110336ce-36a0-4dbe-b285-d7d651fa069a</guid>
    <author>kmulliken@usgs.gov (kmulliken@usgs.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>Volcano Minute — Episodes and Eruptions </title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/observatories/hvo/news/volcano-minute-episodes-and-eruptions?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>Over the last year and a half, Kīlauea’s summit has produced an impressive 49 episodes of lava fountaining—and episode 50 may be just around the corner. Why are these considered episodes instead of separate eruptions?</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Thu, 18 Jun 2026 21:38:29 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>kmulliken@usgs.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">95b0f2ee-8ba1-484e-863e-a0b4963fac3a</guid>
    <author>kmulliken@usgs.gov (kmulliken@usgs.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>USGS: Lithium in Carolinas Could Replace Imports for a Century or More </title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/news/national-news-release/usgs-lithium-carolinas-could-replace-imports-a-century-or-more?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p><strong>RESTON, Va. </strong>— The southern Appalachian region of the eastern United States contains an estimated 1.43 million metric tons of undiscovered, economically recoverable lithium oxide, enough to replace 201 years of U.S. imports at last year’s level, according to new research by the U.S. Geological Survey.&nbsp;</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Thu, 18 Jun 2026 11:46:03 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>jolene_gittens@ios.doi.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">4f454d65-4ba3-43a9-90c2-6d773960b04f</guid>
    <author>jolene_gittens@ios.doi.gov (jolene_gittens@ios.doi.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>Media Alert: Low-level flights to image geology of southern Colorado</title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/news/state-news-release/media-alert-low-level-flights-image-geology-southern-colorado?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p><strong>RESTON, Va. –</strong> The U.S. Geological Survey plans low-level helicopter flights over southern Colorado to image geology using airborne geophysical technology. The survey will begin in June and continue for two months, weather and other flight restrictions permitting.</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Thu, 18 Jun 2026 10:35:11 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>jolene_gittens@ios.doi.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">c200b9a9-b7a5-4245-b2c3-94d92dad75de</guid>
    <author>jolene_gittens@ios.doi.gov (jolene_gittens@ios.doi.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>Explore Global Coastal Research Using the COAWST Applications Catalog </title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/centers/whcmsc/news/explore-global-coastal-research-using-coawst-applications-catalog?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>Around the world,&nbsp;scientists are using the Coupled Ocean-Atmosphere-Waves-Sediment Transport (COAWST) Modeling System to&nbsp;better understand and forecast short-term changes in coastal conditions. To showcase the breadth of this work, the USGS developed the COAWST Applications Catalog—a collection of published COAWST-based studies spanning multiple countries, coastlines, and scientific questions.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Thu, 18 Jun 2026 09:07:14 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>sernst@usgs.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">15d572f4-5485-484b-80c7-8cfd57e06d8d</guid>
    <author>sernst@usgs.gov (sernst@usgs.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>USGS Releases Expedition Report for Samoa Basin Box Coring Effort</title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/programs/cmhrp/news/usgs-releases-expedition-report-samoa-basin-box-coring-effort?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>On leg three of the American Samoa Mapping Project, an interagency-supported hydrograph survey project led by NOAA and in partnership with BOEM, USGS collected box cores and interdisciplinary datasets to inform prospectivity analyses throughout the region.</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Wed, 17 Jun 2026 16:05:44 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>ppearsall@usgs.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">38fd8d50-0583-467e-a576-dad513501428</guid>
    <author>ppearsall@usgs.gov (ppearsall@usgs.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>A More Intelligent World</title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/centers/california-water-science-center/news/a-more-intelligent-world?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>Two scientists from the California Water Science Center will share their work at the 2026 Esri User Conference, highlighting innovative applications of Geographic Information System (GIS) and water science. Their presentations showcase how geospatial tools help advance scientific understanding and support informed resource management.</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Wed, 17 Jun 2026 14:24:37 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>shipra_shukla@ios.doi.gov</dc:creator>
