<item>
  <title>What a Super El Niño could mean for Alaska’s seabirds, salmon, and seas</title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/mission-areas/ecosystems/news/what-a-super-el-nino-could-mean-alaskas-seabirds-salmon-and-seas?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>NOAA has declared an El Niño in June 2026, with a "Super El Niño" expected to peak this winter. USGS researchers are tracking how warming waters threaten Alaska's ecosystems, from seabird die-offs and harmful algal blooms to heat-stressed salmon. USGS science helps reveal the connections between these climate events and the fish and wildlife that Alaskans and ecosystems depend on.</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Mon, 15 Jun 2026 19:35:28 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>sally_house@ios.doi.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">550917e4-b92a-4098-80a1-411adcbffb0e</guid>
    <author>sally_house@ios.doi.gov (sally_house@ios.doi.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>Supporting Endangered Rusty Patched Bumble Bee Recovery Efforts</title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/mission-areas/ecosystems/news/supporting-endangered-rusty-patched-bumble-bee-recovery-efforts?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>Join us for a Pollinator Week edition of <em>Friday's Findings</em> that highlights methods the USGS is developing to find undiscovered populations of the endangered rusty patched bumble bee.<br><br><strong>Date:&nbsp;</strong> Friday, June 26, 2026<br><strong>Time:</strong> &nbsp;2:00-2:30 PM Eastern/11:00 -11:30 AM Pacific<br><strong>Speaker:&nbsp;</strong> Clint Otto, Research Ecologist, USGS Northern Prairie Wildlife Research Center</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Mon, 15 Jun 2026 16:42:31 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>sally_house@ios.doi.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">25e19482-33d8-4c36-a29b-4e007b0abc92</guid>
    <author>sally_house@ios.doi.gov (sally_house@ios.doi.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>The fascinating history of Imperial Geyser</title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/observatories/yvo/news/fascinating-history-imperial-geyser?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>In the far southwest corner of Lower Geyser Basin is Imperial Geyser—a colorful pool that is also a perpetual spouter. &nbsp;The feature seems to have formed in 1927 and for a time was the most spectacular geyser in Yellowstone National Park!</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Mon, 15 Jun 2026 00:30:00 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>mpoland@usgs.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">a5959514-1431-4783-a8a9-7063a05be1b8</guid>
    <author>mpoland@usgs.gov (mpoland@usgs.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>Cooperative Research Unit Awards </title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/programs/cooperative-research-units/news/cooperative-research-unit-awards?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>The Cooperative Research Units Program is excited to announce the winners of our 2026 Outstanding Awards selection for Best Student or Post-Doc led paper, Outstanding MS Student, Outstanding PhD Student, and Outstanding Alumni.&nbsp;</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Fri, 12 Jun 2026 16:03:41 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>tmcconnell@usgs.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">007edfbd-6957-4343-9a7f-a4b7ee133bf1</guid>
    <author>tmcconnell@usgs.gov (tmcconnell@usgs.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>Volcano Minute — The 1926 eruption of Mauna Loa occurred 100 years ago this year </title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/observatories/hvo/news/volcano-minute-1926-eruption-mauna-loa-occurred-100-years-ago-year?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>This past April marked one hundred years since Mauna Loa’s 1926 Southwest Rift Zone eruption — an eruption remembered for its dramatic lava flows, community impacts, and scientific firsts.&nbsp;</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Thu, 11 Jun 2026 22:05:12 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>kmulliken@usgs.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">2b2bdbf2-b89c-4dad-bc60-35e9ec733286</guid>
    <author>kmulliken@usgs.gov (kmulliken@usgs.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>Media Alert: Low-level flights to image geology of eastern North Dakota</title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/news/state-news-release/media-alert-low-level-flights-image-geology-eastern-north-dakota?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p><strong>RESTON, Va.</strong>&nbsp; – The U.S. Geological Survey plans low-level airplane flights over eastern North Dakota and small nearby areas of Minnesota and South Dakota to image geology using airborne geophysical technology. The survey will begin in early June and will continue into the fall, weather and other flight restrictions permitting.&nbsp;</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Thu, 11 Jun 2026 16:14:19 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>seth_amgott@ios.doi.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">06481913-09bc-4509-b244-f01a4e763097</guid>
    <author>seth_amgott@ios.doi.gov (seth_amgott@ios.doi.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>Media Alert: Low-level helicopter flights to image geology of Lake Superior Basin</title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/news/state-news-release/media-alert-low-level-helicopter-flights-image-geology-lake-superior-basin?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p><strong>RESTON, Va</strong>.<strong>&nbsp;</strong>— The U.S. Geological Survey plans low-level helicopter flights over the Lake Superior Basin in western Michigan, northern Wisconsin, and northeastern Minnesota to image geology using airborne geophysical technology. The survey will begin in June and will continue into the fall, weather and other flight restrictions permitting.</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Thu, 11 Jun 2026 14:54:19 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>jason_burton@ios.doi.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">63759e23-41cd-443c-bbf2-822c069c498f</guid>
    <author>jason_burton@ios.doi.gov (jason_burton@ios.doi.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>Volcano Watch — Remembering the 1926 Mauna Loa eruption a century later</title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/observatories/hvo/news/volcano-watch-remembering-1926-mauna-loa-eruption-a-century-later?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>April marked the 100-year anniversary of Mauna Loa’s 1926 Southwest Rift Zone eruption. This eruption is most remembered for the destruction of Ho‘ōpūloa village, a few miles north of Miloliʻi Bay. It also marks the first known instance of aerial photography of an advancing Hawaiian lava flow, and well-organized police-led eruption crowd management.</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Thu, 11 Jun 2026 12:10:46 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>kmulliken@usgs.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">b04fb1c8-3793-40ab-882b-629c56bab53c</guid>
    <author>kmulliken@usgs.gov (kmulliken@usgs.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>Photo &amp; Video Chronology — Kīlauea summit monitoring overflight</title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/observatories/hvo/news/photo-video-chronology-kilauea-summit-monitoring-overflight?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>USGS scientists conduct Kīlauea summit monitoring overflight on June 9, 2026, to document changes to the eruptive vents and crater floor after episode 48 that took place on June 1.&nbsp;</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Wed, 10 Jun 2026 15:10:20 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>kmulliken@usgs.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">1a1e8ee0-789a-45c3-8eef-d69cd1602405</guid>
    <author>kmulliken@usgs.gov (kmulliken@usgs.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>Magnitude-4.7 Earthquake Information Statement</title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/observatories/hvo/news/magnitude-47-earthquake-information-statement?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>On Tuesday, June 9, 10:37 p.m. HST, a magnitude-4.7 earthquake occurred 14 mi (23 km) east of Pāpa‘ikou on the Island of Hawaiʻi at a depth of 24 mi (39 km) below sea level. The earthquake had no apparent impact on either Mauna Loa or Kīlauea volcanoes.&nbsp;</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Wed, 10 Jun 2026 14:07:49 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>kmulliken@usgs.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">11aa6fba-816b-41e1-9f5f-117f0dc78456</guid>
    <author>kmulliken@usgs.gov (kmulliken@usgs.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>USGS Participates in 2026 Native American Fish and Wildlife Society National Conference </title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/programs/climate-adaptation-science-centers/news/usgs-participates-2026-native-american-fish-and?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>USGS staff from multiple centers participated in the 2026 Native American Fish and Wildlife Society’s national annual conference.&nbsp;</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Tue, 9 Jun 2026 09:01:29 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>kmalpeli@usgs.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">1e0a83d9-3a3c-4f2a-bd5d-1ce98b8ed073</guid>
    <author>kmalpeli@usgs.gov (kmalpeli@usgs.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>Species on the Move: Northeast CASC Researchers Discuss Species Range Shift in Recent Podcast Episode</title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/programs/climate-adaptation-science-centers/news/species-move-northeast-casc-researchers-discuss?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>In a recent episode of Ask MIT Climate, a climate-focused podcast of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Northeast CASC Research Ecologist Toni Lyn Morelli and former Northeast CASC Fellow Alexej Sirén discuss how species are responding to a warming climate.&nbsp;</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Mon, 8 Jun 2026 14:40:15 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>cduzet@contractor.usgs.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">b63152a1-57e6-4df3-b1d7-9518017e99e6</guid>
    <author>cduzet@contractor.usgs.gov (cduzet@contractor.usgs.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>Study Reveals That Inland Recreational Fishery Harvest is Quite the Catch</title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/programs/climate-adaptation-science-centers/news/study-reveals-inland-recreational-fishery-harvest?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>New research shows that inland recreational fisheries likely harvest far more fish than previously reported. A recent article in <em>The Conversation</em> summarizes this research and highlights the significant and underestimated role recreational fisheries play in food security, ecosystems, and economies.</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Mon, 8 Jun 2026 14:22:06 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>cduzet@contractor.usgs.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">ced59fd7-49e9-48a8-b096-ad108bedf9c0</guid>
    <author>cduzet@contractor.usgs.gov (cduzet@contractor.usgs.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>USGS and Kazakh hydrogeologists meet to discuss groundwater monitoring and resource management </title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/international-programs/news/usgs-and-kazakh-hydrogeologists-meet-discuss-groundwater-monitoring-and?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>USGS hosted a delegation of scientists from Kazakhstan’s Ministry of Water Resources &amp; Irrigation (MWRI), at the USGS Idaho Water Science Center in Boise (May 11–15, 2026).&nbsp;</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Mon, 8 Jun 2026 08:45:00 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>smieszek@usgs.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">23ec77a9-e4f2-494a-a0db-447270b07bb1</guid>
    <author>smieszek@usgs.gov (smieszek@usgs.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>
<item>
  <title>Young mountains, old rocks: A geological overview of the Teton range</title>
  <link>https://www.usgs.gov/observatories/yvo/news/young-mountains-old-rocks-a-geological-overview-teton-range?utm_source=comms&amp;amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;amp;utm_campaign=news</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p>The Teton Range, just south of Yellowstone National Park, is the youngest mountain range in the Rockies, and possibly North America. The forces that built (and are still actively building) the Tetons differ fundamentally from those that formed the other mountain ranges in the Greater Yellowstone Ecosystem.</p>]]></description>
  <pubDate>Mon, 8 Jun 2026 00:30:00 EDT</pubDate>
  <dc:creator>mpoland@usgs.gov</dc:creator>
  <guid isPermaLink="false">c2e4eaae-f269-4e25-b9b6-d731e1f331ab</guid>
    <author>mpoland@usgs.gov (mpoland@usgs.gov)</author>
  <source url="https://www.usgs.gov/news/all/feed">U.S. Geological Survey</source>
</item>

  </channel>
